<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>THIS IS AN APPLICATION</BOLD> for Judicial Review in respect of a second review decision dated July 31, 2017 issued by the Canada Revenue Agency (the &ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) concluding that the applicant is not entitled to relief from interest or penalties under the taxpayer relief provisions of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.) (the &ldquo;<EM>ITA</EM>&rdquo;):</P>
<P>1. The applicant makes an application for:
<P1>(a) an Order that:
<P2>(i) the decision of the CRA dated July 31, 2017 (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;) be varied; and</P2>
<P2>(ii) the applicant's taxpayer relief request for full interest and penalty cancellation be granted in full;</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) the costs of this Application; and</P1>
<P1>(c) such further and other relief as may be required and this Honourable Court may deem just in the circumstances of this case.</P1></P>
<P>2. The grounds for the application are:
<P1>(a) the <EM>Federal Courts Act</EM>, R.S.C., 1985, c. F-7 (&ldquo;<EM>Federal Courts Act</EM>&rdquo;), as amended, and in particular sections 18 and 18.1;</P1>
<P1>(b) the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985, c. 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp.) (&ldquo;<EM>ITA</EM>&rdquo;) as amended, and in particular subsection 220(3.1);</P1>
<P1>(c) the CRA is a federal board, commission or other tribunal pursuant to the <EM>Federal Courts Act</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(d) the Decision is a second review of the applicant's first request for taxpayer relief, which first request was denied in full by the CRA on December 5, 2014;</P1>
<P1>(e) The Decision considered whether the applicant's financial position and serious emotional and mental distress related to a death in his family and a divorce entitled him to cancellation of penalties and arrears interest relating to a payroll tax debt of Highmark Development Inc. (&ldquo;Highmark&rdquo;) incurred in or around the 2005 and 2006 taxation years for which the CRA alleged the applicant was personally liable in his capacity as a corporate director of Highmark during the material times;</P1>
<P1>(f) The Decision concluded that the applicant failed to demonstrate that his failure to remit Highmark's payroll tax was due to serious emotional and mental distress resulting from his divorce and a death in his family or that he had an inability to pay the ongoing outstanding payroll tax debt as a result of financial hardship. On this basis, the Decision further concluded that the applicant was not entitled to any relief from penalties or interest relating to the payroll tax debt under the taxpayer relief provisions of the <EM>ITA</EM>; and</P1>
<P1>(g) The applicant says that the Decision was unreasonable and in reaching the Decision, the CRA
<P2>(i) erred in law;</P2>
<P2>(ii) erred in its findings of fact;</P2>
<P2>(iii) fettered its discretion;</P2>
<P2>(iv) considered irrelevant factors andfailed to considerrelevant factors;</P2>
<P2>(v) relied on guidelines and policies that are contrary to law; and</P2>
<P2>(vi) committed a palpable andoverridingerror, reviewable by this Court;</P2></P1></P>
<P>3. This application will be supported by the following material:
<P1>(a) the record relating to the Decision (the &ldquo;Record&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(b) affidavit(s) to be filed; and</P1>
<P1>(c) such further and other documentary evidence as counsel may provide and this Honourable Court may allow.</P1></P>
<P>4. The applicant requests that the CRA send a certified copy of the following material that is not in the possession of the applicant but is in the possession of the CRA to the applicant and to the Registry pursuant to Rule 317 of the <EM>Federal Court Rules</EM>:
<P1>(a) the Record and all material relevant to this application.</P1></P>
<P>August 30, 2017</P>
