<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>RESPONDENT'S MEMORANDUM OF FACT AND LAW</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The applicant seeks judicial review of a decision of the Minister of National Revenue in response to his request for taxpayer relief. The Minister exercised discretion not to grant the applicant additional relief.</P>
<P>2. The applicant is a businessman who participated in a series of transactions designed to avoid tax by selling his corporation, transferring shares of other corporations to members of his family, and having all assets held in other corporations' names. He has structured his finances so that nothing is in his name.</P>
<P>3. In 2008, the Minister issued a director's liability assessment against the applicant for Highmark Developments Inc. for $275,787.73, on the basis that he was liable for unpaid payroll remittances of the corporation related to the corporation's 2006 tax year. The amount assessed includes penalties for failure to remit on the missed remittances along with the principal amounts of the missed remittances and arrears interest.</P>
<P>4. The applicant applied for relief from penalties and interest. His request was denied. The Minister concluded that the applicant did not demonstrate that he was prevented from complying with his tax obligations. The request was otherwise denied as there were no circumstances to justify the exercise of the Minister's discretion to grant relief.</P>
<P>5. The Minister's decision was reasonable and there is no basis upon which this court should intervene.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>6. The applicant is a businessman and is associated with eleven Canadian corporations. Through his corporations he is involved various farming operations<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, pages 3&ndash;5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.</P>
<P>7. By letter received on October 1, 2012 the applicant submitted a request for taxpayer relief to the Minister of National Revenue (the &ldquo;Minister&rdquo;) requesting relief of penalties and interest pursuant to subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> in relation to the director's liability assessment was made that was made against the applicant as director of the corporation, Highmark Development Inc., on the basis of medical/emotional distress and financial hardship.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. In response to the initial request, the Minister declined to grant relief to the applicant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. By letter received on October 12, 2016, the applicant requested a second review of his taxpayer relief request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. The decision in response to the applicant's request for a second review of his taxpayer relief request was issued by Mona Khanifar, Tax Payer Relief Team Leader in the Appeals Division of the Vancouver Tax Services Office of the Canada Revenue Agency, as a delegated representative of the Minister of National Revenue for the purposes of subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>. The decision was communicated to the applicant by letter dated July 31, 2017 and is the decision that is the subject of review in the within application.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART II&mdash;POINT IN ISSUE</TI>
<P>11. The issue in this application is whether the Minister's decision is reasonable.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART III&mdash;SUBMISSIONS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Minister's decision is reviewable on a standard of reasonableness</TI>
<P>12. The decision under review is a discretionary decision made under subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, RSC 1985, c 1 (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp), section 220(3.1). [Respondent's Record, Appendix A, Tab 1]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The well-settled standard of review with respect to decisions under subsection 220(3.1) is that of reasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Revenue Agency v Telfer</SOC><CITE>2009 FCA 23</CITE></CASEREF> [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 12], and <CASEREF><SOC>Lanno v Canada (Customs and Revenue Agency)</SOC><CITE>2005 FCA 153</CITE></CASEREF>. [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 9]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. The standard of reasonableness was described in <EM>Dunsmuir</EM> as being &ldquo;concerned mostly with the existence of justification, transparency and intelligibility within the decision-making process.&rdquo; It is a deferential standard that examines &ldquo;whether the decision falls within a range of possible, acceptable outcomes which are defensible in respect of the facts and law.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, para 47 [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 9]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. On judicial review, the court &ldquo;cannot substitute [its] own appreciation of the appropriate solution.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Citizenship and Immigration) v Khosa</SOC><CITE>2009 SCC 12</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2009] 1 SCR 339</CITE><PARANUM>59</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 5]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Rather, it must determine whether the Minister's decision fell within the range of acceptable solutions.</P>
<P>15. The Minister's findings of fact are entitled to a high degree of deference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Khosa</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> note 9 at para 46. [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 5]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The appropriate level of deference requires &ldquo;a respectful attention to the reasons offered or which could be offered in support of a decision&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Newfoundland and Labrador Nurses' Union v Newfoundland and Labrador (Treasury Board)</SOC><CITE>2011 SCC 62</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2011] 3 SCR 708</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 10]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Minister's decision falls within the range of reasonable outcomes</TI>
<P>16. The Minister's decision was reasonable in light of the information put before her.</P>
<P>17. Subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Income Tax Act</EM>, R.S.C. 1985 c.1, (5<SUP>th</SUP> Supp) as amended, section 230(3.1). [Respondent's Record, Appendix A, Tab 1]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> gives the Minister broad discretion to waive or cancel penalties and interest otherwise payable under the Act. The Canada Revenue Agency has developed administrative guidelines to inform the exercise of this discretion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Information Circular IC07, Canada Revenue Agency [Respondent's Record, Appendix A, Tab 3]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. Cancellation of interest may be justified where a taxpayer has been unable to deal with their obligations due to delays on the part of the Minister, extraordinary circumstances, or financial hardship.</P>
<P>19. The decision maker considered each of the grounds cited in support of the applicant's request for relief. The Minister also considered the factual findings that led her to decide not to grant additional relief.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. The applicant claims he was experiencing financial and emotional hardship on the one hand, and then made several promises to pay the debt in full on the other, including in 2007.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, pages 2-3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Nothing prevented the applicant from voluntarily addressing the payroll remittances on time, or addressing the assessment balance in a timely manner.</P>
<P>21. Extraordinary circumstances are situations beyond a taxpayer's control which may have prevented them from making a payment (or otherwise fulfilling an obligation) when due. Examples of extraordinary circumstances include natural disasters, civil disturbances, serious illness or accident, and serious mental or emotional distress. They are situations where it was not possible for the taxpayer to conduct their affairs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cooke v R</SOC><CITE>2009 FC 1161</CITE><PARANUM>18 and 20</PARANUM></CASEREF> [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 7].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. The Minister's finding on this point is well within the range of acceptable outcomes and should stand.</P>
<P>23. The Minister reviewed the applicant's representations and reasonably concluded that there were no grounds for interest relief outside of the grounds named in the guidelines. His conduct did not merit it. The applicant had a history of not paying large amounts owing to the Minister as required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He knowingly allowed interest to accrue on his debt in spite of letters advising same from Canada Revenue Agency.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2, page 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He did not take care in the conduct of his affairs and, indeed, was engaged in a pattern of behavior designed to frustrate the Canada Revenue Agency by promising to pay in full and transferring assets to his family members.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Tribunal Record, Rule 317 certificate, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He did not make a voluntary payment on his debt for ten years, and avoided addressing his obligation for the 2006 taxation year.</P>
<P>24. The applicant also seeks substantive relief from this court. This relief is not available to the applicant. As confirmed by the Federal Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Canada Revenue Agency v Slau Limited</SOC></CASEREF>, subsection 220(3.1) of the <EM>Income Tax Act</EM> &ldquo;simply requires the Minister to exercise the discretion that is provided thereunder and does not require the Minister to bring about any particular result.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada Revenue Agency v Slau</SOC><CITE>2009 FCA 270</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2009 DTC 5167</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>[2010] 1 CTC 15</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [Respondent's Record, Appendix B, Tab 11].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. The Minister considered all of the material and issued a reasonable decision in light of all the facts presented. That decision should be upheld.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART IV&mdash;ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>26. The Respondent seeks an order dismissing this application with costs.</P>
